<dl id="n12138a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12138a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12138a"> 138(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the buttons were there / before the breeches</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The wearing of clothes is in no way natural to men <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> In the Sudan and elsewhere women wear girdles of cowrie shells to give them fertility. It probably was by way of this practice that the use of clothing arose; for women would find that their sexual attractiveness was thereby enhanced. <small> William James Perry, <a name="ORMR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ORMR"><cite title="source">Origin of Magic and Religion</cite></a> (1923) 14-15</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12141i" href="c12all.htm#c12141i">VI.C.12:141(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
